Eureka! Smoking is found to be bad

Ex-smokers are still likely to develop lung cancer

Hillary Stevenson

Staff Writer

On their way to class, thou-
sands of Pitt students carry their
books in one hand and hold onto
a cigarette with the other.

They light up before and
after class, trying to ease them-
selves of the pressures of college
life. Easing stress, they say, out-
weighs the beneﬁts of quitting.

Unfortunately for them,
recent studies by a Pitt professor
suggest that smokers are still
likely to contract lung cancer,
even if they were to quit today.

Dr. Jill Siegfried, associate
professor of pharmacology and
director of basic science at the
Pitt Cancer Institute's Lung
Cancer Center, found that smok-
ing for at least 25 years increas-

es the reproduction of lung cells.
The rapid growth of lung cells
can lead to lung cancer.

The reproduction of lung
cells might begin much sooner
than 25 years, though, she noted.

The growth process begins
with a gastrin-releasing peptide
receptor that is on the surface of
lung cells. These receptors then
capture various hormones. Once
this occurs, lung cells will
divide. The new cells may con-
tinue to bear the gastrin-releas-
ing receptors, which capture
more hormones, eventually
leading to lung disease.

Siegfried said this process is
permanent and could explain
why ‘long-term ex-smokers
develop lung cancer, even if
they hadn't had a cigarette in
years.

"For the ex-smoker, this is a
vicious cycle, because it doesn't
matter if they stopped smoking.
Once the process is activated,
it's permanent," Siegfried said.

She started her research ﬁve
years ago. It has involved 37
subjects. Some subjects . just
started smoking, while others
had smoked for at least 25 years.
Only one subject didn't smoke.

Siegfried warned that this

processmay not apply to only“

smokers. It is possible that it
could occur in anyone who has a
genetic predisposition toward
lung disease or who has con-
tracted lung disease in a way
other than smoking.

Young smokers should pay
attention to ﬁndings such as
these, advised Siegfried.

